00:02:03.222 --> 00:02:05.858 align:start size:88% position:13%
- [Narrator] Man has
waged war on weeds since

00:02:05.858 --> 00:02:08.194
the beginning of agriculture.

00:02:08.194 --> 00:02:11.130
Some weeds are put on
the noxious weed list,

00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:14.734
outlawed and targeted
with chemical sprays.

00:02:15.868 --> 00:02:17.637
- The description of
what a noxious weed is,

00:02:17.637 --> 00:02:21.207
is it's a non native,
very aggressive plant.

00:02:21.207 --> 00:02:24.877
- [Narrator] Leafy spurge,
Russian knapweed and kochia

00:02:24.877 --> 00:02:27.679
have made countless
acres unpalatable

00:02:27.679 --> 00:02:30.582
to cattle, horses and wildlife.

00:02:30.582 --> 00:02:33.019
- Unfortunately,
people have sprayed

00:02:33.019 --> 00:02:35.688 align:start size:88% position:13%
so many herbicides
that kochia's resistant

00:02:35.688 --> 00:02:38.791 align:start size:84% position:16%
to about every
chemical known to man.

00:02:41.294 --> 00:02:44.097
- [Narrator] For these
contract goat herders,

00:02:44.097 --> 00:02:47.166
the trick is not to win
the noxious weed battle

00:02:47.166 --> 00:02:50.603 align:start size:94% position:6%
with herbicides, but to
participate in what nature

00:02:50.603 --> 00:02:53.238
is trying to accomplish.

00:02:53.238 --> 00:02:55.174
- [Greg] You have good soil,
you're gunna have good grass.

00:02:55.174 --> 00:02:57.176
It's pretty much
impossible not to.

00:02:57.176 --> 00:02:59.879 align:start size:97% position:3%
- [Narrator] Recognizing the
importance of the animal,

00:02:59.879 --> 00:03:03.549
plant, soil connection,
these goat herders work

00:03:03.549 --> 00:03:07.520 align:start position:0%
to convert weeds into something
that feeds the soil life.

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:08.988 align:start size:88% position:13%
- The goats just happen
to eat the weeds,

00:03:08.988 --> 00:03:12.257 align:start size:97% position:3%
but, you know, they manage
the cows, the sheep, the deer,

00:03:12.257 --> 00:03:15.394
whatever you happen to be on
there, I mean, that's required

00:03:15.394 --> 00:03:18.264
to have a good, healthy
range, land and soil

00:03:18.264 --> 00:03:19.698
is to actually graze it.

00:03:19.698 --> 00:03:21.801
- [Narrator] So they
bring in goats to eat

00:03:21.801 --> 00:03:26.071
the invasive plant the cattle,
horses and wildlife will not.

00:03:26.071 --> 00:03:27.273
- So these are Cashmere goats.

00:03:27.273 --> 00:03:29.909 align:start size:84% position:16%
They, evolution wise,
come from the top

00:03:29.909 --> 00:03:32.612 align:start size:94% position:6%
of the Himalaya mountains
but a lot of weeds

00:03:32.612 --> 00:03:36.282 align:start size:97% position:3%
come from Eurasia so, you
know, they have a connection

00:03:36.282 --> 00:03:39.051 align:start size:81% position:19%
that cattle and
horses don't have.

00:03:39.051 --> 00:03:42.788 align:start size:97% position:3%
These have the enzymes and
bacteria that they can utilize

00:03:42.788 --> 00:03:46.826 align:start size:97% position:3%
all these insane plants that
cattle and horses can't.

00:03:46.826 --> 00:03:48.527
- [Narrator] So the
goal is to augment

00:03:48.527 --> 00:03:50.797
nature's restoration process.

00:03:51.998 --> 00:03:55.568 align:start size:94% position:6%
- When you have a
disturbance to any ground

00:03:57.003 --> 00:03:59.973
and, it could be a natural
disturbance, like right now

00:03:59.973 --> 00:04:04.043 align:start size:94% position:6%
the floods, hurricane,
drought, fire, that causes

00:04:05.745 --> 00:04:10.049 align:start size:97% position:3%
the ground to be bare, mother
nature is gunna rush in

00:04:10.049 --> 00:04:11.550
and protect that.

00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:14.053
She sees that there's a
wound, like I get a scab.

00:04:14.053 --> 00:04:18.524 align:start size:97% position:3%
That's to protect my
surface and keep my boundary

00:04:18.524 --> 00:04:21.961
of my skin intact and,
so, mother nature does

00:04:21.961 --> 00:04:24.697 align:start size:81% position:19%
the same thing
and who does that?

00:04:24.697 --> 00:04:26.465
Our annual weeds.

00:04:26.465 --> 00:04:28.334
That's their job so they rush in

00:04:28.334 --> 00:04:32.638
so you have cheatgrass
here, kochia, sunflowers,

00:04:32.638 --> 00:04:36.843
lamb's quarters, tumble
weeds, Russian thistle,

00:04:36.843 --> 00:04:40.212
halogeton, all of
those annual weeds.

00:04:40.212 --> 00:04:44.517
That is their job in plant
succession is to rush in

00:04:44.517 --> 00:04:47.119
and cover that wound
and protect the surface

00:04:47.119 --> 00:04:49.122
and hold your water in.

00:04:49.122 --> 00:04:51.224 align:start size:94% position:6%
Next, if you don't do
anything, you're gunna see

00:04:51.224 --> 00:04:54.726 align:start size:84% position:16%
biannual plants,
weeds, which would be

00:04:54.726 --> 00:04:58.664 align:start size:84% position:16%
all of the thistles
except Canada thistle.

00:04:58.664 --> 00:05:02.668 align:start size:94% position:6%
Common mullein,
houndstongue, dyer's woad.

00:05:02.668 --> 00:05:04.837
Takes two years for
it to make a seed

00:05:04.837 --> 00:05:08.874 align:start size:97% position:3%
and get that root going down
so it's starting to build

00:05:08.874 --> 00:05:11.677 align:start size:84% position:16%
soil structure and
bring other things up.

00:05:11.677 --> 00:05:13.078
So that's the biannual.

00:05:13.078 --> 00:05:14.747 align:start size:84% position:16%
You have bare ground,
annual, biannual,

00:05:14.747 --> 00:05:16.582
then you start to
see perennials.

00:05:16.582 --> 00:05:19.284
Often you'll see the
perennial weeds first.

00:05:19.284 --> 00:05:22.722
Leafy spurge, Russian
knapweed, bindweed,

00:05:24.824 --> 00:05:28.294
dalmation toadflax, all of
those that are a big problem.

00:05:28.294 --> 00:05:30.630
Canada thistle,
you'll see those.

00:05:30.630 --> 00:05:34.467
And then you'll see grass
and then, and this is like,

00:05:34.467 --> 00:05:38.337
doing nothing, so, in a dry
environment like Wyoming,

00:05:38.337 --> 00:05:42.007
this could be 400 years
for this to progress

00:05:42.007 --> 00:05:46.179 align:start position:0%
but it's the natural progression
and then you see brush

00:05:47.713 --> 00:05:50.048
and then you see trees.

00:05:50.048 --> 00:05:52.118 align:start size:97% position:3%
- [Narrator] It is the plant
world's way of bringing

00:05:52.118 --> 00:05:55.688
trace minerals up to the
surface where the biology

00:05:55.688 --> 00:05:57.490
in the soil needs it.

00:05:57.490 --> 00:05:59.992
- Some of these other noxious
weeds we have in the area,

00:05:59.992 --> 00:06:02.494
one of the reasons they can
survive so well is they have

00:06:02.494 --> 00:06:05.297 align:start size:84% position:16%
a tremendous root
system and they can go

00:06:05.297 --> 00:06:07.499 align:start size:94% position:6%
so much further down
than those normal grasses

00:06:07.499 --> 00:06:11.069 align:start size:88% position:13%
and normal vegetation
does that they can reach

00:06:11.069 --> 00:06:12.872
way down there and
so they'll pull up

00:06:12.872 --> 00:06:15.141 align:start size:97% position:3%
the nutrients that the
other grasses can't get to.

00:06:15.141 --> 00:06:16.642
- So, all of these
plant, you know,

00:06:16.642 --> 00:06:20.079 align:start size:97% position:3%
they have different purposes
and different skills.

00:06:20.079 --> 00:06:23.816 align:start size:88% position:13%
The Astragalus species,
which are vetches,

00:06:23.816 --> 00:06:27.987 align:start position:0%
are the only plant that can
bring selenium up from the soil.

00:06:28.855 --> 00:06:30.489
The only plant.

00:06:30.489 --> 00:06:32.458
So they all do their
thing and all the roots

00:06:32.458 --> 00:06:34.259
go to different depths.

00:06:34.259 --> 00:06:37.296 align:start position:0%
Russian knapweed and the
knapweeds pull up a lot of zinc.

00:06:37.296 --> 00:06:40.932 align:start size:94% position:6%
- So, by either trampling
them on the ground

00:06:40.932 --> 00:06:42.735 align:start size:84% position:16%
or on the surface, and
then trampling them

00:06:42.735 --> 00:06:45.438 align:start size:94% position:6%
and putting that nutrients
back into the topsoil,

00:06:45.438 --> 00:06:49.642 align:start size:94% position:6%
or by an animal eating
that vegetation, you know,

00:06:49.642 --> 00:06:51.177 align:start size:84% position:16%
as the whole nutrient
cycle starts over

00:06:51.177 --> 00:06:54.280 align:start size:94% position:6%
with nutrients that nobody
else is able to get to.

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:57.516 align:start size:97% position:3%
- Goats like Russian knapweed
so you have two choices

00:06:57.516 --> 00:07:00.652
if you have a herd
of cattle or horses

00:07:00.652 --> 00:07:02.354 align:start size:94% position:6%
and you have a whole
bunch of Russian knapweed.

00:07:02.354 --> 00:07:05.090
One is you kill it all or go
get something that eats it...

00:07:05.090 --> 00:07:06.158
(laughs)

00:07:06.158 --> 00:07:07.292
and use it.

00:07:07.292 --> 00:07:09.628 align:start size:88% position:13%
It's a natural resource,
why not use it?

00:07:09.628 --> 00:07:11.964
All I do is recycle it.

00:07:11.964 --> 00:07:14.533 align:start size:84% position:16%
- Come on nanny,
nanny, nanny, nannies!

00:07:14.533 --> 00:07:16.769 align:start size:97% position:3%
- [Narrator] Greg and
Carolina are actually raising

00:07:16.769 --> 00:07:19.805 align:start size:88% position:13%
meat goats on leafy
spurge, which is one of

00:07:19.805 --> 00:07:22.408 align:start size:88% position:13%
the worst weed
problems rancher's face

00:07:22.408 --> 00:07:24.142
in the Devil's Tower area.

00:07:24.142 --> 00:07:27.046
- If there's spurge,
they'll eat the spurge

00:07:27.046 --> 00:07:28.580
